# The `Throwable` hierarchy — checked vs unchecked

## Two branches under `Throwable`

- **`Error`** — fatal JVM problems (`OutOfMemoryError`) — don't catch
- **`Exception`** (not runtime) — **checked**
- **`RuntimeException`** — **unchecked**, mostly bugs

## The compile-time contract

| Kind | Base | Enforced? | Example |
|---|---|---|---|
| Checked | `Exception` | catch or `throws` | `IOException` |
| Unchecked | `RuntimeException` | no | `NullPointerException` |
| Error | `Error` | no | `OutOfMemoryError` |

## Which to use

- **Checked** — recoverable (file missing) · **unchecked** — bugs (null, bad arg)
- Modern Java **leans unchecked** — checked don't compose with streams/lambdas
